    "summary": "Abstract The Tonlé Sap floodplain in Cambodia supports one of the most productive freshwater ecosystems in the world. Flooded forests surrounding the lake play a crucial ecological role by providing fish habitats, regulating nutrient cycles, and supporting biodiversity and local livelihoods. However, these forests have experienced significant degradation due to agricultural expansion, illegal logging, hydrological changes, and climate variability. This review synthesizes existing scientific literature on the status, drivers, impacts, and management of flooded forest degradation in the Tonlé Sap floodplain. Remote sensing studies indicate substantial forest loss over recent decades, while hydrological alterations driven by upstream dam construction and climate change threaten ecosystem stab"
